form.longName: PhenX PX121703 - Depressive Symptoms - Depression In Dementia
form.preferredDefinition: The Mood and Feelings Questionnaire (MFQ) is a 13-item, self-administered questionnaire on depressive symptoms. Each item is rated on a 3-point scale (0 = not true; 1 = sometimes true; 2 = true), and total scores range from 0-26, with higher scores indicating more severe depression symptoms.

question.questionText: Has your relative been feeling anxious this past week? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Anxiety_Past_Week)
Has s/he been worrying about things s/he may not ordinarily worry about, or ruminating over things that may not be that important? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Anxiety_Unusual)
Has your relative had an anxious, tense, distressed, or apprehensive expression? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Anxiety_Family_History)
Has your relative been feeling down, sad, or blue this past week? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Sadness_Past_Week)
For how long each day? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Sadness_Past_Week_Duration)
Has s/he been crying at all? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Sadness_Crying)
How many days out of the past week has s/he been feeling like this? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Sadness_Crying_Past_Week)
For how long each day? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Sadness_Crying_Duration)

If a pleasant event were to occur today (i.e., going out with spouse, friends, seeing grandchildren), would your relative be able to enjoy it fully, or might his/her mood get in the way of his/her interest in the event or activity? Does your relative's mood affect his/her ability to enjoy activities that used to give him/her pleasure? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Reactivity_Affect_Hobbies)

If a pleasant event were to occur today (i.e., going out with spouse, friends, seeing grandchildren), would your relative be able to enjoy it fully, or might his/her mood get in the way of his/her interest in the event or activity? Does your relative's mood affect his/her surroundings? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Reactivity_Affect_Surroundings)

If a pleasant event were to occur today (i.e., going out with spouse, friends, seeing grandchildren), would your relative be able to enjoy it fully, or might his/her mood get in the way of his/her interest in the event or activity? Does your relative's mood affect his/her feelings for family and friends? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Reactivity_Affect_Friends_Family)
Has your relative felt short-tempered or easily annoyed this past week? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Irritability_Short_Temper)
Has s/he been feeling irritable, impatient, or angry this week? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Irritability_Irritable_Impatient_Angry)
Has your relative been so fidgety or restless this past week that s/he was unable to sit still for at least an hour? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Agitation_Past_Week)
Was your relative so physically agitated that you or others noticed it? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Agitation_Noticeable)

Agitation may include such behaviors as playing with one's hands, hair, hand-wringing, hair-pulling, and/or lip-biting: have you observed any such behavior in your relative during the past week? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Agitation_Symptoms)

Has your relative been talking or moving more slowly than is normal for him/her? This may include: slowness of thoughts and speech, delayed response to your questions, decreased motor activity and/or reactions. (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Retardation)
In the past week, has your relative had indigestion? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Indigestion)
In the past week, has your relative had constipation? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Constipation)
In the past week, has your relative had diarrhea? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Diarrhea)
In the past week, has your relative had stomach cramps? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Stomach_Cramps)
In the past week, has your relative had belching? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Belching)
In the past week, has your relative had joint pain? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Joint_Paint)
In the past week, has your relative had backaches? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Backaches)
In the past week, has your relative had muscles aches? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Muscle_Aches)
In the past week, has your relative had frequent urination? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Urination)
In the past week, has your relative had sweating? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Sweating)
In the past week, has your relative had headaches? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Headaches)
In the past week, has your relative had heart palpitations? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Heart_Palpitations)
In the past week, has your relative had hyperventilation (shortness of breath)? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Physical_Complaints_Hyperventilation)
How has your relative been spending his/her time this past week (not including work and chores)? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Acute_Loss_Interest_Behavior)
Has your relative felt interested in his/her usual activities and hobbies? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Acute_Loss_Interest_Hobbies)
Has your relative spent any less time engaging in these activities? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Acute_Loss_Interest_Hobbies_Assessment)

If s/he is not as interested, or has not been that engaged in activities during the past week: Has your relative had to push him/herself to do the things s/he normally enjoys? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Acute_Loss_Interest_Participation)
Has your relative stopped doing anything s/he used to do? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Acute_Loss_Interest_Stop)
Can s/he look forward to anything or has s/he lost interest in many of the hobbies from which s/he used to derive pleasure? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Acute_Loss_Interest_Motivation)
How has your relative's appetite been this past week compared to normal? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Appetite_Loss_Past_Week)
Has it decreased at all? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Appetite_Loss)
Has your relative felt less hungry or had to remind him/herself to eat? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Appetite_Loss_Hunger)
Have others had to urge or force him/her to eat? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Appetite_Loss_Others)
Has your relative lost any weight in the past month that s/he has not meant to or been trying to lose? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Weight_Loss_Past_Month_Unintentional)
Are your relative's clothes any looser on him/her? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Weight_Loss_Past_Month_Clothes)
If weight loss is associated with present illness (i.e., not due to diet or exercise): how many pounds has s/he lost? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Weight_Loss_Illness_Amount)
How has your relative's energy been this past week compared to normal? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Lack_Energy_Past_Week)
Has s/he been tired all the time? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Lack_Energy_Tired)
Has s/he asked to take naps because of fatigue? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Lack_Energy_Naps)

This week, has your relative had any of following symptoms due to lack of energy only (not due to physical problems): heaviness in limbs, back, or head? felt like s/he is dragging through the day? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Lack_Energy_Symptoms)
Has your relative been fatigued more easily this week? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Lack_Energy_Fatigue)

Regarding your relative's mood (his/her feelings and symptoms of depression), is there any part of the day in which s/he usually feels better or worse? (or does it not make any difference, or vary according to the day or situation?) (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Diurnal_Variation_Mood)
If yes to a difference in mood during the day: Is your relative's depression worse in the morning or the evening? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Diurnal_Variation_Mood_Time)
If worse in the morning: Is this a mild or a very noticeable difference? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Diurnal_Variation_Mood_Difference)
Has your relative had any trouble falling asleep this past week? (Depression_Dementia_Relative_Sleep_Difficulty_Past_Week)

protocol.preferredDefinition: The Mood and Feelings Questionnaire (MFQ) is a 13-item, self-administered questionnaire on depressive symptoms. Each item is rated on a 3-point scale (0 = not true; 1 = sometimes true; 2 = true), and total scores range from 0-26, with higher scores indicating more severe depression symptoms.

form.preferredDefinition: The participant is asked to recall physical activities he/she engaged in during the last 4 weeks. The self-administered questionnaire addresses specific activities and asks whether the person has engaged in the activity. If the participant has engaged in the activity, he/she is instructed to answer how many times a week and how many hours total in the week. The Community Health Activity Models Program for Seniors (CHAMPS) codebook is used to score the results and determine the calories expended per week and hours per week engaged in physical activity.
